ng feature of the system and why mass incarceration emerged as a new racial management strategy. This book reviews the history of race and criminology and explores the impact of racist colonial legacies on the organization of criminal justice institutions. Using a macrostructural perspective, students will learn to contextualize issues of race, crime, and criminal justice. Topics include:How “coloniality” explains the practices that reproduce racial hierarchiesThe birth of social science and social programs from the legacies of racial scienceThe defining role of geography and geographical conquest in the continuation of mass incarcerationThe emergence of the logics of crime control, the War on Drugs, the redefinition of federal law enforcement, and the reallocation of state resources toward prison building, policing, and incarcerationHow policing, courts, and punishment perpetuate the colonial order through their institutional structures and policies Race and Crime will help students understand how everyday practices of punishment and surveillance are employed in and through the police, courts, and community to create and shape the geographies of injustice in the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aHuman geographyzUnited States. 0aImprisonmentzUnited States. 0aRacism in criminologyzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  acolonial.  acolonialism.  acolonies.  acrime and punishment.  acrime.  acriminal justice.  acriminals.  acriminology.  aeurope.  aeuropean history.  agovernment.  aimprisonment.  ajail.  ajustice system.  amass incarceration.  apolice system.  apolice.  apolicing.  apost colonial.  aprison.  arace issues.  aracial management.  aracial sta